I just had this Clash in Fastest mode. It was extremely easy. I think it must be exciting in Shortest or Reverse.

Interestingly, there are apparently two ambiguities, that are reflected both in the statement and the tests and validators: 

1) For your function shared_letters, we can write either:

def shared_letters(a, b):
    return any(x==y for x in a for y in b)

or:

def shared_letters(a, b):
    return any(x==y for x,y in zip(a,b)

Both versions pass all tests and validators even though they are clearly not equivalent.

2) Both of these two loops pass all tests and validators, even though the checks are in different order:

for i in range(len(a)):
    if len(a[i]) != len(b[i]): return 'some of the corresponding words not the same length'
    if shared_letters(a[i], b[i]): return 'shared letters in corresponding words'

for i in range(len(a)):
    if len(a[i]) != len(b[i]): return 'some of the corresponding words not the same length'
for i in range(len(a)):
    if shared_letters(a[i], b[i]): return 'shared letters in corresponding words'

I assume the tests and validators were designed on purpose to give more freedom for the implementation. Congrats!
